## Summary

Skill issue but I spent a significant amount of time today debugging something like `use(getPromise())` in a React component. React displayed this error, and ended up suspending again when state changed for the first time elsewhere in the component despite my `getPromise` function using a module level cache. I previously used `use` with Promises and this error message was useful, but I couldn't solve the issue for quite a while this time. My `getPromise` function looked something like this:

```tsx
const bySlug = new Map<string, Promise<PostWithContent>>();

export async function getPostBySlug(slug: string): Promise<Post> {
  const maybePromise = bySlug.get(slug);
  if (maybePromise) {
    return maybePromise;
  }

  const loadPromise = (async () => {
    const { default: content } = await import(
      `../../posts/${slug}.mdx`
    );
    return content;
  })();

  bySlug.set(slug, loadPromise);

  return loadPromise;
}
```

There is a cache so it reuses the same promise each call. However, I eventually checked if `getPostBySlug(slug) === getPostBySlug(slug)`, noticed it was false, and realized that my component was marked as `async` despite not using async/await – likely from an earlier refactor. While the inner promise is cached, marking a function with `async` always returns a new Promise instance.

I changed the error message to hint at this issue. I believe humans and AI will do a better job debugging issues with this hint.

